GNSS ZOE M8B Arduino Library 1.0.0
This is a library for the SGNSS ZOE M8B Module
SparkFun_u-blox_GNSS_Arduino_Library.h
Go to the documentation of this file.

16 from a u-blox GPS module. Works with most modules from u-blox including
17 the Zed-F9P, NEO-M8P-2, NEO-M9N, ZOE-M8Q, SAM-M8Q, and many others.

59// Uncomment the next line (or add SFE_UBLOX_REDUCED_PROG_MEM as a compiler directive) to reduce the amount of program
60// memory used by the library #define SFE_UBLOX_REDUCED_PROG_MEM // Uncommenting this line will delete the minor debug
61// messages to save memory
62
63// The code just about fills the program memory on the ATmega328P (Arduino Uno), so let's delete the minor debug
64// messages anyway
65#if !defined(SFE_UBLOX_REDUCED_PROG_MEM) && defined(ARDUINO_ARCH_AVR)
66#define SFE_UBLOX_REDUCED_PROG_MEM
67#endif

71// Define a digital pin to aid debugging
72// Leave set to -1 if not needed
73const int debugPin = -1;
74
75// Global Status Returns
76typedef enum
77{
78 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_SUCCESS,
79 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_FAIL,
80 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_CRC_FAIL,
81 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_TIMEOUT,
82 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_COMMAND_NACK, // Indicates that the command was unrecognised, invalid or that the module is too
83 // busy to respond
84 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_OUT_OF_RANGE,
85 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_INVALID_ARG,
86 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_INVALID_OPERATION,
87 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_MEM_ERR,
88 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_HW_ERR,
89 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_DATA_SENT, // This indicates that a 'set' was successful
90 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_DATA_RECEIVED, // This indicates that a 'get' (poll) was successful
91 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_I2C_COMM_FAILURE,
92 SFE_UBLOX_STATUS_DATA_OVERWRITTEN // This is an error - the data was valid but has been or _is being_ overwritten by
93 // another packet
94} sfe_ublox_status_e;
95
96// ubxPacket validity
97typedef enum
98{
99 SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_VALID,
100 SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_VALID,
101 SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED,
102 SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_NOTACKNOWLEDGED // This indicates that we received a NACK
103} sfe_ublox_packet_validity_e;
104
105// Identify which packet buffer is in use:
106// packetCfg (or a custom packet), packetAck or packetBuf
107// packetAuto is used to store expected "automatic" messages
108typedef enum
109{
110 SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_PACKETCFG,
111 SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_PACKETACK,
112 SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_PACKETBUF,
113 SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_PACKETAUTO
114} sfe_ublox_packet_buffer_e;
115
116// Define a struct to allow selective logging / processing of NMEA messages
117// Set the individual bits to pass the NMEA messages to the file buffer and/or processNMEA
118// Setting bits.all will pass all messages to the file buffer and processNMEA
119typedef struct
120{
121 union {
122 uint32_t all;
123 struct
124 {
125 uint32_t all : 1;
126 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_DTM : 1;
127 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GAQ : 1;
128 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GBQ : 1;
129 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GBS : 1;
130 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GGA : 1;
131 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GLL : 1;
132 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GLQ : 1;
133 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GNQ : 1;
134 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GNS : 1;
135 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GPQ : 1;
136 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GQQ : 1;
137 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GRS : 1;
138 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GSA : 1;
139 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GST : 1;
140 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_GSV : 1;
141 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_RLM : 1;
142 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_RMC : 1;
143 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_TXT : 1;
144 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_VLW : 1;
145 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_VTG : 1;
146 uint32_t UBX_NMEA_ZDA : 1;
147 } bits;
148 };
149} sfe_ublox_nmea_filtering_t;
150
151// Define an enum to make it easy to enable/disable selected NMEA messages for logging / processing
152typedef enum
153{
154 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_ALL = 0x00000001,
155 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_DTM = 0x00000002,
156 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GAQ = 0x00000004,
157 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GBQ = 0x00000008,
158 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GBS = 0x00000010,
159 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GGA = 0x00000020,
160 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GLL = 0x00000040,
161 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GLQ = 0x00000080,
162 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GNQ = 0x00000100,
163 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GNS = 0x00000200,
164 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GPQ = 0x00000400,
165 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GQQ = 0x00000800,
166 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GRS = 0x00001000,
167 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GSA = 0x00002000,
168 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GST = 0x00004000,
169 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_GSV = 0x00008000,
170 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_RLM = 0x00010000,
171 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_RMC = 0x00020000,
172 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_TXT = 0x00040000,
173 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_VLW = 0x00080000,
174 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_VTG = 0x00100000,
175 SFE_UBLOX_FILTER_NMEA_ZDA = 0x00200000
176} sfe_ublox_nmea_filtering_e;

178// Registers
179const uint8_t UBX_SYNCH_1 = 0xB5;
180const uint8_t UBX_SYNCH_2 = 0x62;
181
182// The following are UBX Class IDs. Descriptions taken from ZED-F9P Interface Description Document page 32, NEO-M8P
183// Interface Description page 145
184const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_NAV =
185 0x01; // Navigation Results Messages: Position, Speed, Time, Acceleration, Heading, DOP, SVs used
186const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_RXM = 0x02; // Receiver Manager Messages: Satellite Status, RTC Status
187const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_INF =
188 0x04; // Information Messages: Printf-Style Messages, with IDs such as Error, Warning, Notice
189const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_ACK = 0x05; // Ack/Nak Messages: Acknowledge or Reject messages to UBX-CFG input messages
190const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_CFG = 0x06; // Configuration Input Messages: Configure the receiver.
191const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_UPD =
192 0x09; // Firmware Update Messages: Memory/Flash erase/write, Reboot, Flash identification, etc.
193const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_MON = 0x0A; // Monitoring Messages: Communication Status, CPU Load, Stack Usage, Task Status
194const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_AID =
195 0x0B; //(NEO-M8P ONLY!!!) AssistNow Aiding Messages: Ephemeris, Almanac, other A-GPS data input
196const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_TIM = 0x0D; // Timing Messages: Time Pulse Output, Time Mark Results
197const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_ESF =
198 0x10; //(NEO-M8P ONLY!!!) External Sensor Fusion Messages: External Sensor Measurements and Status Information
199const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_MGA = 0x13; // Multiple GNSS Assistance Messages: Assistance data for various GNSS
200const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_LOG = 0x21; // Logging Messages: Log creation, deletion, info and retrieval
201const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_SEC = 0x27; // Security Feature Messages
202const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_HNR =
203 0x28; //(NEO-M8P ONLY!!!) High Rate Navigation Results Messages: High rate time, position speed, heading
204const uint8_t UBX_CLASS_NMEA = 0xF0; // NMEA Strings: standard NMEA strings
205
206// Class: CFG
207// The following are used for configuration. Descriptions are from the ZED-F9P Interface Description pg 33-34 and
208// NEO-M9N Interface Description pg 47-48
209const uint8_t UBX_CFG_ANT = 0x13; // Antenna Control Settings. Used to configure the antenna control settings
210const uint8_t UBX_CFG_BATCH = 0x93; // Get/set data batching configuration.
211const uint8_t UBX_CFG_CFG = 0x09; // Clear, Save, and Load Configurations. Used to save current configuration
212const uint8_t UBX_CFG_DAT = 0x06; // Set User-defined Datum or The currently defined Datum
213const uint8_t UBX_CFG_DGNSS = 0x70; // DGNSS configuration
214const uint8_t UBX_CFG_ESFALG = 0x56; // ESF alignment
215const uint8_t UBX_CFG_ESFA = 0x4C; // ESF accelerometer
216const uint8_t UBX_CFG_ESFG = 0x4D; // ESF gyro
217const uint8_t UBX_CFG_GEOFENCE = 0x69; // Geofencing configuration. Used to configure a geofence
218const uint8_t UBX_CFG_GNSS = 0x3E; // GNSS system configuration
219const uint8_t UBX_CFG_HNR = 0x5C; // High Navigation Rate
220const uint8_t UBX_CFG_INF = 0x02; // Depending on packet length, either: poll configuration for one protocol, or
221 // information message configuration
222const uint8_t UBX_CFG_ITFM = 0x39; // Jamming/Interference Monitor configuration
223const uint8_t UBX_CFG_LOGFILTER = 0x47; // Data Logger Configuration
224const uint8_t UBX_CFG_MSG = 0x01; // Poll a message configuration, or Set Message Rate(s), or Set Message Rate
225const uint8_t UBX_CFG_NAV5 =
226 0x24; // Navigation Engine Settings. Used to configure the navigation engine including the dynamic model.
227const uint8_t UBX_CFG_NAVX5 = 0x23; // Navigation Engine Expert Settings
228const uint8_t UBX_CFG_NMEA = 0x17; // Extended NMEA protocol configuration V1
229const uint8_t UBX_CFG_ODO = 0x1E; // Odometer, Low-speed COG Engine Settings
230const uint8_t UBX_CFG_PM2 = 0x3B; // Extended power management configuration
231const uint8_t UBX_CFG_PMS = 0x86; // Power mode setup
232const uint8_t UBX_CFG_PRT = 0x00; // Used to configure port specifics. Polls the configuration for one I/O Port, or Port
233 // configuration for UART ports, or Port configuration for USB port, or Port
234 // configuration for SPI port, or Port configuration for DDC port
235const uint8_t UBX_CFG_PWR = 0x57; // Put receiver in a defined power state
236const uint8_t UBX_CFG_RATE = 0x08; // Navigation/Measurement Rate Settings. Used to set port baud rates.
237const uint8_t UBX_CFG_RINV = 0x34; // Contents of Remote Inventory
238const uint8_t UBX_CFG_RST = 0x04; // Reset Receiver / Clear Backup Data Structures. Used to reset device.
239const uint8_t UBX_CFG_RXM = 0x11; // RXM configuration
240const uint8_t UBX_CFG_SBAS = 0x16; // SBAS configuration
241const uint8_t UBX_CFG_TMODE3 = 0x71; // Time Mode Settings 3. Used to enable Survey In Mode
242const uint8_t UBX_CFG_TP5 = 0x31; // Time Pulse Parameters
243const uint8_t UBX_CFG_USB = 0x1B; // USB Configuration
244const uint8_t UBX_CFG_VALDEL = 0x8C; // Used for config of higher version u-blox modules (ie protocol v27 and above).
245 // Deletes values corresponding to provided keys/ provided keys with a transaction
246const uint8_t UBX_CFG_VALGET =
247 0x8B; // Used for config of higher version u-blox modules (ie protocol v27 and above). Configuration Items
248const uint8_t UBX_CFG_VALSET =
249 0x8A; // Used for config of higher version u-blox modules (ie protocol v27 and above). Sets values corresponding to
250 // provided key-value pairs/ provided key-value pairs within a transaction.
251
252// Class: NMEA
253// The following are used to enable NMEA messages. Descriptions come from the NMEA messages overview in the ZED-F9P
254// Interface Description
255const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_MSB = 0xF0; // All NMEA enable commands have 0xF0 as MSB. Equal to UBX_CLASS_NMEA
256const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_DTM = 0x0A; // GxDTM (datum reference)
257const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GAQ = 0x45; // GxGAQ (poll a standard message (if the current talker ID is GA))
258const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GBQ = 0x44; // GxGBQ (poll a standard message (if the current Talker ID is GB))
259const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GBS = 0x09; // GxGBS (GNSS satellite fault detection)
260const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GGA = 0x00; // GxGGA (Global positioning system fix data)
261const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GLL = 0x01; // GxGLL (latitude and long, whith time of position fix and status)
262const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GLQ = 0x43; // GxGLQ (poll a standard message (if the current Talker ID is GL))
263const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GNQ = 0x42; // GxGNQ (poll a standard message (if the current Talker ID is GN))
264const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GNS = 0x0D; // GxGNS (GNSS fix data)
265const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GPQ = 0x40; // GxGPQ (poll a standard message (if the current Talker ID is GP))
266const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GQQ = 0x47; // GxGQQ (poll a standard message (if the current Talker ID is GQ))
267const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GRS = 0x06; // GxGRS (GNSS range residuals)
268const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GSA = 0x02; // GxGSA (GNSS DOP and Active satellites)
269const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GST = 0x07; // GxGST (GNSS Pseudo Range Error Statistics)
270const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GSV = 0x03; // GxGSV (GNSS satellites in view)
271const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_RLM = 0x0B; // GxRMC (Return link message (RLM))
272const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_RMC = 0x04; // GxRMC (Recommended minimum data)
273const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_TXT = 0x41; // GxTXT (text transmission)
274const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_VLW = 0x0F; // GxVLW (dual ground/water distance)
275const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_VTG = 0x05; // GxVTG (course over ground and Ground speed)
276const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_ZDA = 0x08; // GxZDA (Time and Date)
277
278// The following are used to configure the NMEA protocol main talker ID and GSV talker ID
279const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_MAINTALKERID_NOTOVERRIDDEN = 0x00; // main talker ID is system dependent
280const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_MAINTALKERID_GP = 0x01; // main talker ID is GPS
281const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_MAINTALKERID_GL = 0x02; // main talker ID is GLONASS
282const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_MAINTALKERID_GN = 0x03; // main talker ID is combined receiver
283const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_MAINTALKERID_GA = 0x04; // main talker ID is Galileo
284const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_MAINTALKERID_GB = 0x05; // main talker ID is BeiDou
285const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GSVTALKERID_GNSS = 0x00; // GNSS specific Talker ID (as defined by NMEA)
286const uint8_t UBX_NMEA_GSVTALKERID_MAIN = 0x01; // use the main Talker ID
287
288// Class: HNR
289// The following are used to configure the HNR message rates
290const uint8_t UBX_HNR_ATT = 0x01; // HNR Attitude
291const uint8_t UBX_HNR_INS = 0x02; // HNR Vehicle Dynamics
292const uint8_t UBX_HNR_PVT = 0x00; // HNR PVT
293
294// Class: INF
295// The following are used to configure INF UBX messages (information messages). Descriptions from UBX messages overview
296// (ZED_F9P Interface Description Document page 34)
297const uint8_t UBX_INF_CLASS = 0x04; // All INF messages have 0x04 as the class
298const uint8_t UBX_INF_DEBUG = 0x04; // ASCII output with debug contents
299const uint8_t UBX_INF_ERROR = 0x00; // ASCII output with error contents
300const uint8_t UBX_INF_NOTICE = 0x02; // ASCII output with informational contents
301const uint8_t UBX_INF_TEST = 0x03; // ASCII output with test contents
302const uint8_t UBX_INF_WARNING = 0x01; // ASCII output with warning contents
303
304// Class: LOG
305// The following are used to configure LOG UBX messages (loggings messages). Descriptions from UBX messages overview
306// (ZED_F9P Interface Description Document page 34)
307const uint8_t UBX_LOG_CREATE = 0x07; // Create Log File
308const uint8_t UBX_LOG_ERASE = 0x03; // Erase Logged Data
309const uint8_t UBX_LOG_FINDTIME =
310 0x0E; // Find index of a log entry based on a given time, or response to FINDTIME requested
311const uint8_t UBX_LOG_INFO = 0x08; // Poll for log information, or Log information
312const uint8_t UBX_LOG_RETRIEVEPOSEXTRA = 0x0F; // Odometer log entry
313const uint8_t UBX_LOG_RETRIEVEPOS = 0x0B; // Position fix log entry
314const uint8_t UBX_LOG_RETRIEVESTRING = 0x0D; // Byte string log entry
315const uint8_t UBX_LOG_RETRIEVE = 0x09; // Request log data
316const uint8_t UBX_LOG_STRING = 0x04; // Store arbitrary string on on-board flash
317
318// Class: MGA
319// The following are used to configure MGA UBX messages (Multiple GNSS Assistance Messages). Descriptions from UBX
320// messages overview (ZED_F9P Interface Description Document page 34)
321const uint8_t UBX_MGA_ACK_DATA0 = 0x60; // Multiple GNSS Acknowledge message
322const uint8_t UBX_MGA_ANO = 0x20; // Multiple GNSS AssistNow Offline assistance - NOT SUPPORTED BY THE ZED-F9P! "The
323 // ZED-F9P supports AssistNow Online only."
324const uint8_t UBX_MGA_BDS_EPH = 0x03; // BDS Ephemeris Assistance
325const uint8_t UBX_MGA_BDS_ALM = 0x03; // BDS Almanac Assistance
326const uint8_t UBX_MGA_BDS_HEALTH = 0x03; // BDS Health Assistance
327const uint8_t UBX_MGA_BDS_UTC = 0x03; // BDS UTC Assistance
328const uint8_t UBX_MGA_BDS_IONO = 0x03; // BDS Ionospheric Assistance
329const uint8_t UBX_MGA_DBD = 0x80; // Either: Poll the Navigation Database, or Navigation Database Dump Entry
330const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GAL_EPH = 0x02; // Galileo Ephemeris Assistance
331const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GAL_ALM = 0x02; // Galileo Almanac Assitance
332const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GAL_TIMOFFSET = 0x02; // Galileo GPS time offset assistance
333const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GAL_UTC = 0x02; // Galileo UTC Assistance
334const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GLO_EPH = 0x06; // GLONASS Ephemeris Assistance
335const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GLO_ALM = 0x06; // GLONASS Almanac Assistance
336const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GLO_TIMEOFFSET = 0x06; // GLONASS Auxiliary Time Offset Assistance
337const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GPS_EPH = 0x00; // GPS Ephemeris Assistance
338const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GPS_ALM = 0x00; // GPS Almanac Assistance
339const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GPS_HEALTH = 0x00; // GPS Health Assistance
340const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GPS_UTC = 0x00; // GPS UTC Assistance
341const uint8_t UBX_MGA_GPS_IONO = 0x00; // GPS Ionosphere Assistance
342const uint8_t UBX_MGA_INI_POS_XYZ = 0x40; // Initial Position Assistance
343const uint8_t UBX_MGA_INI_POS_LLH = 0x40; // Initial Position Assitance
344const uint8_t UBX_MGA_INI_TIME_UTC = 0x40; // Initial Time Assistance
345const uint8_t UBX_MGA_INI_TIME_GNSS = 0x40; // Initial Time Assistance
346const uint8_t UBX_MGA_INI_CLKD = 0x40; // Initial Clock Drift Assitance
347const uint8_t UBX_MGA_INI_FREQ = 0x40; // Initial Frequency Assistance
348const uint8_t UBX_MGA_INI_EOP = 0x40; // Earth Orientation Parameters Assistance
349const uint8_t UBX_MGA_QZSS_EPH = 0x05; // QZSS Ephemeris Assistance
350const uint8_t UBX_MGA_QZSS_ALM = 0x05; // QZSS Almanac Assistance
351const uint8_t UBX_MGA_QZAA_HEALTH = 0x05; // QZSS Health Assistance

353// Class: MON
354// The following are used to configure the MON UBX messages (monitoring messages). Descriptions from UBX messages
355// overview (ZED_F9P Interface Description Document page 35)
356const uint8_t UBX_MON_COMMS = 0x36; // Comm port information
357const uint8_t UBX_MON_GNSS = 0x28; // Information message major GNSS selection
358const uint8_t UBX_MON_HW2 = 0x0B; // Extended Hardware Status
359const uint8_t UBX_MON_HW3 = 0x37; // HW I/O pin information
360const uint8_t UBX_MON_HW = 0x09; // Hardware Status
361const uint8_t UBX_MON_IO = 0x02; // I/O Subsystem Status
362const uint8_t UBX_MON_MSGPP = 0x06; // Message Parse and Process Status
363const uint8_t UBX_MON_PATCH = 0x27; // Output information about installed patches
364const uint8_t UBX_MON_RF = 0x38; // RF information
365const uint8_t UBX_MON_RXBUF = 0x07; // Receiver Buffer Status
366const uint8_t UBX_MON_RXR = 0x21; // Receiver Status Information
367const uint8_t UBX_MON_TXBUF = 0x08; // Transmitter Buffer Status. Used for query tx buffer size/state.
368const uint8_t UBX_MON_VER = 0x04; // Receiver/Software Version. Used for obtaining Protocol Version.
369
370// Class: NAV
371// The following are used to configure the NAV UBX messages (navigation results messages). Descriptions from UBX
372// messages overview (ZED_F9P Interface Description Document page 35-36)
373const uint8_t UBX_NAV_ATT = 0x05; // Vehicle "Attitude" Solution
374const uint8_t UBX_NAV_CLOCK = 0x22; // Clock Solution
375const uint8_t UBX_NAV_DOP = 0x04; // Dilution of precision
376const uint8_t UBX_NAV_EOE = 0x61; // End of Epoch
377const uint8_t UBX_NAV_GEOFENCE = 0x39; // Geofencing status. Used to poll the geofence status
378const uint8_t UBX_NAV_HPPOSECEF =
379 0x13; // High Precision Position Solution in ECEF. Used to find our positional accuracy (high precision).
380const uint8_t UBX_NAV_HPPOSLLH =
381 0x14; // High Precision Geodetic Position Solution. Used for obtaining lat/long/alt in high precision
382const uint8_t UBX_NAV_ODO = 0x09; // Odometer Solution
383const uint8_t UBX_NAV_ORB = 0x34; // GNSS Orbit Database Info
384const uint8_t UBX_NAV_POSECEF = 0x01; // Position Solution in ECEF
385const uint8_t UBX_NAV_POSLLH = 0x02; // Geodetic Position Solution
386const uint8_t UBX_NAV_PVT = 0x07; // All the things! Position, velocity, time, PDOP, height, h/v accuracies, number of
387 // satellites. Navigation Position Velocity Time Solution.
388const uint8_t UBX_NAV_PVAT = 0x17; // Navigation position velocity attitude time solution (ZED-F9R only)
389const uint8_t UBX_NAV_RELPOSNED = 0x3C; // Relative Positioning Information in NED frame
390const uint8_t UBX_NAV_RESETODO = 0x10; // Reset odometer
391const uint8_t UBX_NAV_SAT = 0x35; // Satellite Information
392const uint8_t UBX_NAV_SIG = 0x43; // Signal Information
393const uint8_t UBX_NAV_STATUS = 0x03; // Receiver Navigation Status
394const uint8_t UBX_NAV_SVIN = 0x3B; // Survey-in data. Used for checking Survey In status
395const uint8_t UBX_NAV_TIMEBDS = 0x24; // BDS Time Solution
396const uint8_t UBX_NAV_TIMEGAL = 0x25; // Galileo Time Solution
397const uint8_t UBX_NAV_TIMEGLO = 0x23; // GLO Time Solution
398const uint8_t UBX_NAV_TIMEGPS = 0x20; // GPS Time Solution
399const uint8_t UBX_NAV_TIMELS = 0x26; // Leap second event information
400const uint8_t UBX_NAV_TIMEUTC = 0x21; // UTC Time Solution
401const uint8_t UBX_NAV_VELECEF = 0x11; // Velocity Solution in ECEF
402const uint8_t UBX_NAV_VELNED = 0x12; // Velocity Solution in NED
403const uint8_t UBX_NAV_AOPSTATUS = 0x60; // AssistNow Autonomous status
404
405// Class: RXM
406// The following are used to configure the RXM UBX messages (receiver manager messages). Descriptions from UBX messages
407// overview (ZED_F9P Interface Description Document page 36)
408const uint8_t UBX_RXM_MEASX = 0x14; // Satellite Measurements for RRLP
409const uint8_t UBX_RXM_PMREQ = 0x41; // Requests a Power Management task (two differenent packet sizes)
410const uint8_t UBX_RXM_RAWX = 0x15; // Multi-GNSS Raw Measurement Data
411const uint8_t UBX_RXM_RLM = 0x59; // Galileo SAR Short-RLM report (two different packet sizes)
412const uint8_t UBX_RXM_RTCM = 0x32; // RTCM input status
413const uint8_t UBX_RXM_SFRBX = 0x13; // Broadcast Navigation Data Subframe
414const uint8_t UBX_RXM_SPARTN = 0x33; // SPARTN input status

432 // Flash, Backup File Creation Acknowledge, System Restored from Backup

434// The following are used to enable RTCM messages

436const uint8_t UBX_RTCM_1005 = 0x05; // Stationary RTK reference ARP

446const uint8_t UBX_RTCM_4072_0 = 0xFE; // Reference station PVT (ublox proprietary RTCM message)
447const uint8_t UBX_RTCM_4072_1 = 0xFD; // Additional reference station information (ublox proprietary RTCM message)

497enum dynModel // Possible values for the dynamic platform model, which provide more accuract position output for the
498 // situation. Description extracted from ZED-F9P Integration Manual
499{
500 DYN_MODEL_PORTABLE = 0, // Applications with low acceleration, e.g. portable devices. Suitable for most situations.
501 // 1 is not defined
502 DYN_MODEL_STATIONARY = 2, // Used in timing applications (antenna must be stationary) or other stationary
503 // applications. Velocity restricted to 0 m/s. Zero dynamics assumed.
504 DYN_MODEL_PEDESTRIAN, // Applications with low acceleration and speed, e.g. how a pedestrian would move. Low
505 // acceleration assumed.
506 DYN_MODEL_AUTOMOTIVE, // Used for applications with equivalent dynamics to those of a passenger car. Low vertical
507 // acceleration assumed
508 DYN_MODEL_SEA, // Recommended for applications at sea, with zero vertical velocity. Zero vertical velocity assumed.
509 // Sea level assumed.
510 DYN_MODEL_AIRBORNE1g, // Airborne <1g acceleration. Used for applications with a higher dynamic range and greater
511 // vertical acceleration than a passenger car. No 2D position fixes supported.
512 DYN_MODEL_AIRBORNE2g, // Airborne <2g acceleration. Recommended for typical airborne environments. No 2D position
513 // fixes supported.
514 DYN_MODEL_AIRBORNE4g, // Airborne <4g acceleration. Only recommended for extremely dynamic environments. No 2D
515 // position fixes supported.
516 DYN_MODEL_WRIST, // Not supported in protocol versions less than 18. Only recommended for wrist worn applications.
517 // Receiver will filter out arm motion.
518 DYN_MODEL_BIKE, // Supported in protocol versions 19.2. (not available in all products)
519 DYN_MODEL_MOWER, // Added in HPS 1.21 (not available in all products)
520 DYN_MODEL_ESCOOTER, // Added in HPS 1.21 (not available in all products)
521 DYN_MODEL_UNKNOWN = 255 // getDynamicModel will return 255 if sendCommand fails
522};

590#ifndef MAX_PAYLOAD_SIZE
591// v2.0: keep this for backwards-compatibility, but this is largely superseded by setPacketCfgPayloadSize
592#define MAX_PAYLOAD_SIZE 256 // We need ~220 bytes for getProtocolVersion on most ublox modules
593//#define MAX_PAYLOAD_SIZE 768 //Worst case: UBX_CFG_VALSET packet with 64 keyIDs each with 64 bit values
594#endif
595
596// For storing SPI bytes received during sendSpiCommand
597#define SFE_UBLOX_SPI_BUFFER_SIZE 128
598
599// Default maximum NMEA byte count
600// maxNMEAByteCount was set to 82: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NMEA_0183#Message_structure
601// but the u-blox HP (RTK) GGA messages are 88 bytes long
602// The user can adjust maxNMEAByteCount by calling setMaxNMEAByteCount
603#define SFE_UBLOX_MAX_NMEA_BYTE_COUNT 88
604
605//-=-=-=-=- UBX binary specific variables
606struct ubxPacket
607{
608 uint8_t cls;
609 uint8_t id;
610 uint16_t len; // Length of the payload. Does not include cls, id, or checksum bytes
611 uint16_t counter; // Keeps track of number of overall bytes received. Some responses are larger than 255 bytes.
612 uint16_t startingSpot; // The counter value needed to go past before we begin recording into payload array
613 uint8_t *payload; // We will allocate RAM for the payload if/when needed.
614 uint8_t checksumA; // Given to us from module. Checked against the rolling calculated A/B checksums.
615 uint8_t checksumB;
616 sfe_ublox_packet_validity_e valid; // Goes from NOT_DEFINED to VALID or NOT_VALID when checksum is checked
617 sfe_ublox_packet_validity_e classAndIDmatch; // Goes from NOT_DEFINED to VALID or NOT_VALID when the Class and ID
618 // match the requestedClass and requestedID
619};
620
621// Struct to hold the results returned by getGeofenceState (returned by UBX-NAV-GEOFENCE)
622typedef struct
623{
624 uint8_t status; // Geofencing status: 0 - Geofencing not available or not reliable; 1 - Geofencing active
625 uint8_t numFences; // Number of geofences
626 uint8_t combState; // Combined (logical OR) state of all geofences: 0 - Unknown; 1 - Inside; 2 - Outside
627 uint8_t states[4]; // Geofence states: 0 - Unknown; 1 - Inside; 2 - Outside
628} geofenceState;
629
630// Struct to hold the current geofence parameters
631typedef struct
632{
633 uint8_t numFences; // Number of active geofences
634 int32_t lats[4]; // Latitudes of geofences (in degrees * 10^-7)
635 int32_t longs[4]; // Longitudes of geofences (in degrees * 10^-7)
636 uint32_t rads[4]; // Radii of geofences (in m * 10^-2)
637} geofenceParams_t;
638
639// Struct to hold the module software version
640typedef struct
641{
642 uint8_t versionLow; // Loaded from getProtocolVersion().
643 uint8_t versionHigh;
644 bool moduleQueried;
645} moduleSWVersion_t;

648 {0, 0, 31, 60, 91, 121, 152, 182, 213, 244, 274, 305, 335, 335, 335, 335},
649 {0, 0, 31, 59, 90, 120, 151, 181, 212, 243, 273, 304, 334, 334, 334, 334},
650 {0, 0, 31, 59, 90, 120, 151, 181, 212, 243, 273, 304, 334, 334, 334, 334},
651 {0, 0, 31, 59, 90, 120, 151, 181, 212, 243, 273, 304, 334, 334, 334, 334},
652};

654class SFE_UBLOX_GNSS
655{
656 public:
657 SFE_UBLOX_GNSS(void);
658
659// A default of 250ms for maxWait seems fine for I2C but is not enough for SerialUSB.
660// If you know you are only going to be using I2C / Qwiic communication, you can
661// safely reduce defaultMaxWait to 250.
662#ifndef defaultMaxWait // Let's allow the user to define their own value if they want to
663#define defaultMaxWait 1100
664#endif
665
666 // New in v2.0: allow the payload size for packetCfg to be changed
667 void setPacketCfgPayloadSize(size_t payloadSize); // Set packetCfgPayloadSize
668
669 // Begin communication with the GNSS. Advanced users can assume success if required. Useful if the port is already
670 // outputting messages at high navigation rate. Begin will then return true if "signs of life" have been seen:
671 // reception of _any_ valid UBX packet or _any_ valid NMEA header. By default use the default I2C address, and use
672 // Wire port
673 bool begin(TwoWire &wirePort = Wire, uint8_t deviceAddress = 0x42, uint16_t maxWait = defaultMaxWait,
674 bool assumeSuccess = false); // Returns true if module is detected
675 // serialPort needs to be perviously initialized to correct baud rate
676 bool begin(Stream &serialPort, uint16_t maxWait = defaultMaxWait,
677 bool assumeSuccess = false); // Returns true if module is detected
678 // SPI - supply instance of SPIClass, chip select pin and SPI speed (in Hz)
679 bool begin(SPIClass &spiPort, uint8_t csPin, uint32_t spiSpeed, uint16_t maxWait = defaultMaxWait,
680 bool assumeSuccess = false);
681
682 void end(void); // Stop all automatic message processing. Free all used RAM
683
684 void setI2CpollingWait(uint8_t newPollingWait_ms); // Allow the user to change the I2C polling wait if required
685 void setSPIpollingWait(uint8_t newPollingWait_ms); // Allow the user to change the SPI polling wait if required
686
687 // Set the max number of bytes set in a given I2C transaction
688 uint8_t i2cTransactionSize = 32; // Default to ATmega328 limit
689
690 // Control the size of the internal I2C transaction amount
691 void setI2CTransactionSize(uint8_t bufferSize);
692 uint8_t getI2CTransactionSize(void);
693
694 // Support for platforms like ESP32 which do not support multiple I2C restarts
695 // If _i2cStopRestart is true, endTransmission will always use a stop. If false, a restart will be used where
696 // needed. The default value for _i2cStopRestart is set in the class instantiation code.
697 void setI2cStopRestart(bool stop)
698 {
699 _i2cStopRestart = stop;
700 };
701 bool getI2cStopRestart(void)
702 {
703 return (_i2cStopRestart);
704 };
705
706 // Control the size of the spi buffer. If the buffer isn't big enough, we'll start to lose bytes
707 // That we receive if the buffer is full!
708 void setSpiTransactionSize(uint8_t bufferSize);
709 uint8_t getSpiTransactionSize(void);
710
711 // Control the size of maxNMEAByteCount
712 void setMaxNMEAByteCount(int8_t newMax);
713 int8_t getMaxNMEAByteCount(void);
714
715 // Returns true if device answers on _gpsI2Caddress address or via Serial
716 bool isConnected(uint16_t maxWait = defaultMaxWait);
717
718// Enable debug messages using the chosen Serial port (Stream)
719// Boards like the RedBoard Turbo use SerialUSB (not Serial).
720// But other boards like the SAMD51 Thing Plus use Serial (not SerialUSB).
721// These lines let the code compile cleanly on as many SAMD boards as possible.
722#if defined(ARDUINO_ARCH_SAMD) // Is this a SAMD board?
723#if defined(USB_VID) // Is the USB Vendor ID defined?
724#if (USB_VID == 0x1B4F) // Is this a SparkFun board?
725#if !defined(ARDUINO_SAMD51_THING_PLUS) & \
726 !defined(ARDUINO_SAMD51_MICROMOD) // If it is not a SAMD51 Thing Plus or SAMD51 MicroMod
727 void enableDebugging(Stream &debugPort = SerialUSB,
728 bool printLimitedDebug =
729 false); // Given a port to print to, enable debug messages. Default to all, not limited.
730#else
731 void enableDebugging(Stream &debugPort = Serial,
732 bool printLimitedDebug =
733 false); // Given a port to print to, enable debug messages. Default to all, not limited.
734#endif
735#else
736 void enableDebugging(Stream &debugPort = Serial,
737 bool printLimitedDebug =
738 false); // Given a port to print to, enable debug messages. Default to all, not limited.
739#endif
740#else
741 void enableDebugging(Stream &debugPort = Serial,
742 bool printLimitedDebug =
743 false); // Given a port to print to, enable debug messages. Default to all, not limited.
744#endif
745#else
746 void enableDebugging(Stream &debugPort = Serial,
747 bool printLimitedDebug =
748 false); // Given a port to print to, enable debug messages. Default to all, not limited.
749#endif
750
751 void disableDebugging(void); // Turn off debug statements
752 void debugPrint(char *message); // Safely print debug statements
753 void debugPrintln(char *message); // Safely print debug statements
754 const char *statusString(sfe_ublox_status_e stat); // Pretty print the return value
755
756 // Check for the arrival of new I2C/Serial data
757
758 void disableUBX7Fcheck(
759 bool disabled = true); // When logging RAWX data, we need to be able to disable the "7F" check in checkUbloxI2C
760
761 // Changed in V1.8.1: provides backward compatibility for the examples that call checkUblox directly
762 // Will default to using packetCfg to look for explicit autoPVT packets so they get processed correctly by
763 // processUBX
764 bool checkUblox(uint8_t requestedClass = 0, uint8_t requestedID = 0); // Checks module with user selected commType
765
766 bool checkUbloxI2C(ubxPacket *incomingUBX, uint8_t requestedClass,
767 uint8_t requestedID); // Method for I2C polling of data, passing any new bytes to process()
768 bool checkUbloxSerial(ubxPacket *incomingUBX, uint8_t requestedClass,
769 uint8_t requestedID); // Method for serial polling of data, passing any new bytes to process()
770 bool checkUbloxSpi(ubxPacket *incomingUBX, uint8_t requestedClass,
771 uint8_t requestedID); // Method for spi polling of data, passing any new bytes to process()
772
773 // Process the incoming data
774
775 void process(uint8_t incoming, ubxPacket *incomingUBX, uint8_t requestedClass,
776 uint8_t requestedID); // Processes NMEA and UBX binary sentences one byte at a time
777 void processNMEA(char incoming)
778 __attribute__((weak)); // Given a NMEA character, do something with it. User can overwrite if desired to use
779 // something like tinyGPS or MicroNMEA libraries
780 void processRTCMframe(uint8_t incoming); // Monitor the incoming bytes for start and length bytes
781 void processRTCM(uint8_t incoming)
782 __attribute__((weak)); // Given rtcm byte, do something with it. User can overwrite if desired to pipe bytes to
783 // radio, internet, etc.
784 void processUBX(uint8_t incoming, ubxPacket *incomingUBX, uint8_t requestedClass,
785 uint8_t requestedID); // Given a character, file it away into the uxb packet structure
786 void processUBXpacket(ubxPacket *msg); // Once a packet has been received and validated, identify this packet's
787 // class/id and update internal flags
788
789 // Send I2C/Serial/SPI commands to the module
790
791 void calcChecksum(ubxPacket *msg); // Sets the checksumA and checksumB of a given messages
792 sfe_ublox_status_e sendCommand(ubxPacket *outgoingUBX, uint16_t maxWait = defaultMaxWait,
793 bool expectACKonly = false); // Given a packet and payload, send everything including
794 // CRC bytes, return true if we got a response
795 sfe_ublox_status_e sendI2cCommand(ubxPacket *outgoingUBX, uint16_t maxWait = defaultMaxWait);
796 void sendSerialCommand(ubxPacket *outgoingUBX);
797 void sendSpiCommand(ubxPacket *outgoingUBX);
798
799 void printPacket(ubxPacket *packet, bool alwaysPrintPayload = false); // Useful for debugging
800
801 // After sending a message to the module, wait for the expected response (data+ACK or just data)
802
803 sfe_ublox_status_e waitForACKResponse(ubxPacket *outgoingUBX, uint8_t requestedClass, uint8_t requestedID,
804 uint16_t maxTime = defaultMaxWait); // Poll the module until a config packet
805 // and an ACK is received, or just an ACK
806 sfe_ublox_status_e waitForNoACKResponse(
807 ubxPacket *outgoingUBX, uint8_t requestedClass, uint8_t requestedID,
808 uint16_t maxTime = defaultMaxWait); // Poll the module until a config packet is received

813 // Push (e.g.) RTCM data directly to the module
814 // Warning: this function does not check that the data is valid. It is the user's responsibility to ensure the data
815 // is valid before pushing. Default to using a restart between transmissions. But processors like ESP32 seem to need
816 // a stop (#30). Set stop to true to use a stop instead.
817 bool pushRawData(uint8_t *dataBytes, size_t numDataBytes, bool stop = false);
818
819// Push MGA AssistNow data to the module.
820// Check for UBX-MGA-ACK responses if required (if mgaAck is YES or ENQUIRE).
821// Wait for maxWait millis after sending each packet (if mgaAck is NO).
822// Return how many bytes were pushed successfully.
823// If skipTime is true, any UBX-MGA-INI-TIME_UTC or UBX-MGA-INI-TIME_GNSS packets found in the data will be skipped,
824// allowing the user to override with their own time data with setUTCTimeAssistance.
825// offset allows a sub-set of the data to be sent - starting from offset.
826#define defaultMGAdelay 7 // Default to waiting for 7ms between each MGA message
827 size_t pushAssistNowData(const String &dataBytes, size_t numDataBytes,
828 sfe_ublox_mga_assist_ack_e mgaAck = SFE_UBLOX_MGA_ASSIST_ACK_NO,
829 uint16_t maxWait = defaultMGAdelay);
830 size_t pushAssistNowData(const uint8_t *dataBytes, size_t numDataBytes,
831 sfe_ublox_mga_assist_ack_e mgaAck = SFE_UBLOX_MGA_ASSIST_ACK_NO,
832 uint16_t maxWait = defaultMGAdelay);
833 size_t pushAssistNowData(bool skipTime, const String &dataBytes, size_t numDataBytes,
834 sfe_ublox_mga_assist_ack_e mgaAck = SFE_UBLOX_MGA_ASSIST_ACK_NO,
835 uint16_t maxWait = defaultMGAdelay);
836 size_t pushAssistNowData(bool skipTime, const uint8_t *dataBytes, size_t numDataBytes,
837 sfe_ublox_mga_assist_ack_e mgaAck = SFE_UBLOX_MGA_ASSIST_ACK_NO,
838 uint16_t maxWait = defaultMGAdelay);
839 size_t pushAssistNowData(size_t offset, bool skipTime, const String &dataBytes, size_t numDataBytes,
840 sfe_ublox_mga_assist_ack_e mgaAck = SFE_UBLOX_MGA_ASSIST_ACK_NO,
841 uint16_t maxWait = defaultMGAdelay);
842 size_t pushAssistNowData(size_t offset, bool skipTime, const uint8_t *dataBytes, size_t numDataBytes,
843 sfe_ublox_mga_assist_ack_e mgaAck = SFE_UBLOX_MGA_ASSIST_ACK_NO,
844 uint16_t maxWait = defaultMGAdelay);

876// Read the whole navigation data base. The receiver will send all available data from its internal database.
877// Data is written to dataBytes. Set maxNumDataBytes to the (maximum) size of dataBytes.
878// If the database exceeds maxNumDataBytes, the excess bytes will be lost.
879// The function returns the number of database bytes written to dataBytes.
880// The return value will be equal to maxNumDataBytes if excess data was received.
881// The function will timeout after maxWait milliseconds - in case the final UBX-MGA-ACK was missed.
882#define defaultNavDBDMaxWait 3100
883 size_t readNavigationDatabase(uint8_t *dataBytes, size_t maxNumDataBytes, uint16_t maxWait = defaultNavDBDMaxWait);

1123 // checkUblox when you want to perform an update

2049 uint8_t _gpsI2Caddress = 0x42; // Default 7-bit unshifted address of the ublox 6/7/8/M8/F9 series
2050 // This can be changed using the ublox configuration software
2051
2052 bool _printDebug = false; // Flag to print the serial commands we are sending to the Serial port for debug
2053 bool _printLimitedDebug =
2054 false; // Flag to print limited debug messages. Useful for I2C debugging or high navigation rates
2055
2056 bool ubx7FcheckDisabled = false; // Flag to indicate if the "7F" check should be ignored in checkUbloxI2C
2057
2058 sfe_ublox_nmea_filtering_t
2059 _logNMEA; // Flags to indicate which NMEA messages should be added to the file buffer for logging
2060 sfe_ublox_nmea_filtering_t _processNMEA; // Flags to indicate which NMEA messages should be passed to processNMEA
2061
2062 // The packet buffers
2063 // These are pointed at from within the ubxPacket
2064 uint8_t payloadAck[2]; // Holds the requested ACK/NACK
2065 uint8_t payloadBuf[2]; // Temporary buffer used to screen incoming packets or dump unrequested packets
2066 size_t packetCfgPayloadSize = 0; // Size for the packetCfg payload. .begin will set this to MAX_PAYLOAD_SIZE if
2067 // necessary. User can change with setPacketCfgPayloadSize
2068 uint8_t *payloadCfg = NULL;
2069 uint8_t *payloadAuto = NULL;
2070
2071 uint8_t *spiBuffer =
2072 NULL; // A buffer to store any bytes being recieved back from the device while we are sending via SPI
2073 uint8_t spiBufferIndex = 0; // Index into the SPI buffer
2074 uint8_t spiTransactionSize = SFE_UBLOX_SPI_BUFFER_SIZE; // Default size of the SPI buffer
2075
2076 // Init the packet structures and init them with pointers to the payloadAck, payloadCfg, payloadBuf and payloadAuto
2077 // arrays
2078 ubxPacket packetAck = {
2079 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, payloadAck, 0, 0, SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED, SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED};
2080 ubxPacket packetBuf = {
2081 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, payloadBuf, 0, 0, SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED, SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED};
2082 ubxPacket packetCfg = {
2083 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, payloadCfg, 0, 0, SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED, SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED};
2084 ubxPacket packetAuto = {
2085 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, payloadAuto, 0, 0, SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED, SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_VALIDITY_NOT_DEFINED};
2086
2087 // Flag if this packet is unrequested (and so should be ignored and not copied into packetCfg or packetAck)
2088 bool ignoreThisPayload = false;
2089
2090 // Identify which buffer is in use
2091 // Data is stored in packetBuf until the requested class and ID can be validated
2092 // If a match is seen, data is diverted into packetAck or packetCfg
2093 //"Automatic" messages which have RAM allocated for them are diverted into packetAuto
2094 sfe_ublox_packet_buffer_e activePacketBuffer = SFE_UBLOX_PACKET_PACKETBUF;
2095
2096 // Limit checking of new data to every X ms
2097 // If we are expecting an update every X Hz then we should check every quarter that amount of time
2098 // Otherwise we may block ourselves from seeing new data
2099 uint8_t i2cPollingWait = 100; // Default to 100ms. Adjusted when user calls setNavigationFrequency() or
2100 // setHNRNavigationRate() or setMeasurementRate()
2101 uint8_t i2cPollingWaitNAV = 100; // We need to record the desired polling rate for standard nav messages
2102 uint8_t i2cPollingWaitHNR = 100; // and for HNR too so we can set i2cPollingWait to the lower of the two
2103
2104 // The SPI polling wait is a little different. checkUbloxSpi will delay for this amount before returning if
2105 // there is no data waiting to be read. This prevents waitForACKResponse from pounding the SPI bus too hard.
2106 uint8_t spiPollingWait =
2107 9; // Default to 9ms; waitForACKResponse delays for 1ms on top of this. User can adjust with setSPIPollingWait.
2108
2109 unsigned long lastCheck = 0;
2110
2111 uint16_t ubxFrameCounter; // Count all UBX frame bytes. [Fixed header(2bytes), CLS(1byte), ID(1byte),
2112 // length(2bytes), payload(x bytes), checksums(2bytes)]
2113 uint8_t
2114 rollingChecksumA; // Rolls forward as we receive incoming bytes. Checked against the last two A/B checksum bytes
2115 uint8_t
2116 rollingChecksumB; // Rolls forward as we receive incoming bytes. Checked against the last two A/B checksum bytes
2117
2118 int8_t nmeaByteCounter; // Count all NMEA message bytes.
2119 // Abort NMEA message reception if nmeaByteCounter exceeds maxNMEAByteCount.
2120 // The user can adjust maxNMEAByteCount by calling setMaxNMEAByteCount
2121 int8_t maxNMEAByteCount = SFE_UBLOX_MAX_NMEA_BYTE_COUNT;
2122 uint8_t nmeaAddressField[6]; // NMEA Address Field - includes the start character (*)
2123 bool logThisNMEA(); // Return true if we should log this NMEA message
2124 bool processThisNMEA(); // Return true if we should pass this NMEA message to processNMEA
2125 bool isNMEAHeaderValid(); // Return true if the six byte NMEA header appears valid. Used to set _signsOfLife
2126
2127 bool isThisNMEAauto(); // Check if the NMEA message (in nmeaAddressField) is "auto" (i.e. has RAM allocated for it)
2128 bool doesThisNMEAHaveCallback(); // Do we need to copy the data into the callback copy?
2129 uint8_t *getNMEAWorkingLengthPtr(); // Get a pointer to the working copy length
2130 uint8_t *getNMEAWorkingNMEAPtr(); // Get a pointer to the working copy NMEA data
2131 uint8_t *getNMEACompleteLengthPtr(); // Get a pointer to the complete copy length
2132 uint8_t *getNMEACompleteNMEAPtr(); // Get a pointer to the complete copy NMEA data
2133 uint8_t *getNMEACallbackLengthPtr(); // Get a pointer to the callback copy length
2134 uint8_t *getNMEACallbackNMEAPtr(); // Get a pointer to the callback copy NMEA data
2135 uint8_t getNMEAMaxLength(); // Get the maximum length of this NMEA message
2136 nmeaAutomaticFlags *getNMEAFlagsPtr(); // Get a pointer to the flags
2137
2138 uint16_t rtcmLen = 0;
2139
2140 // Flag to prevent reentry into checkCallbacks
2141 // Prevent badness if the user accidentally calls checkCallbacks from inside a callback
2142 volatile bool checkCallbacksReentrant = false;
2143
2144 // Support for data logging
2145 uint8_t *ubxFileBuffer = NULL; // Pointer to the file buffer. RAM is allocated for this if required in .begin
2146 uint16_t fileBufferSize =
2147 0; // The size of the file buffer. This can be changed by calling setFileBufferSize _before_ .begin
2148 uint16_t fileBufferHead; // The incoming byte is written into the file buffer at this location
2149 uint16_t fileBufferTail; // The next byte to be read from the buffer will be read from this location
2150 uint16_t fileBufferMaxAvail = 0; // The maximum number of bytes the file buffer has contained. Handy for checking
2151 // the buffer is large enough to handle all the incoming data.
2152 bool createFileBuffer(void); // Create the file buffer. Called by .begin
2153 uint16_t fileBufferSpaceAvailable(void); // Check how much space is available in the buffer
2154 uint16_t fileBufferSpaceUsed(void); // Check how much space is used in the buffer
2155 bool storePacket(ubxPacket *msg); // Add a UBX packet to the file buffer
2156 bool storeFileBytes(uint8_t *theBytes, uint16_t numBytes); // Add theBytes to the file buffer
2157 void writeToFileBuffer(uint8_t *theBytes, uint16_t numBytes); // Write theBytes to the file buffer
2158
2159 // Support for platforms like ESP32 which do not support multiple I2C restarts
2160 // If _i2cStopRestart is true, endTransmission will always use a stop. If false, a restart will be used where
2161 // needed. The default value for _i2cStopRestart is set in the class instantiation code.
2162 bool _i2cStopRestart;
2163
2164 // Storage just in case the user tries to push a single byte using pushRawBytes
2165 bool _pushSingleByte = false;
2166 uint8_t _pushThisSingleByte;

2170 bool _signsOfLife;
